title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W 629-6 .44mag. Stainless 4" Mountain Gun with S&W Wood Presentation Case, and Two Sets of Grips
postcontent: S&W 629-6 .44mag. Stainless 4" Mountain Gun with S&W Wood Presentation Case, a set of Pachmyr Grips, & a set of Altamont Silverblack Combat Grips. Shes a beautiful collector wheel gun with minor fading to laser etched areas. She is 1 of 1000 that were made during the 3rd and last run of the 629 Mountain Gun.The 629 Mountain Gun was a limited run/edition revolver that was also done for the model 29. They were produced to be a "lightweight" backcountry carry gun. There were only 3 production runs of it between 1989 to 2005, making them sought after by collectors. Total production number for both models was 15000 with 6 dashes/changes on the 629 during the timeframe of production. My 629-6 Mountain Gun was in the 3rd and last production run. There were only 1000 629's produced during that run. The Mountain Gun had square butts until dash 4, then went to round butts. It came with a tapered 4" Barrel that was 2ozs lighter than the 629 Classic. Mountain gun also had beveled/curved areas around the end of the cylinder for smoother placement of the revolver back into a holster. The MG had a smooth textured trigger, whereas the Classic had the target style serrations texture. MG maintained wide hammer. MG front sight post was all black, as well as rear adj. sight post. The classic had red front sight post with white outlined rear post. The dash-6 came with the lock. I've got a case, leather paddle holster, set of Pachmyr Grips, & set of Altamont SilverBlack Grips.  $850 cash for the MG alone with Pachmyr Grips & a hard case. $950 cash for the above plus the presentation case and extra grips, and $1100 trade. CWP preferred, but SCDL with no felonies will be required.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Kel-Tec PF-9 and 2 Magazines
postcontent: A few important things to say before I even make any statements about the gun.If you live outside the state of Ohio, Federal Law requires me to ship the gun to a licensed dealwer in your home state.  If we have to do that, you will be expected to pay the shipping charges and any fees charged by your local FFL, associated with the transfer.If you would not pass a NICS, please don't contact me.  It is a violation of Federal Law, for me to know that you are ineligible to own a gun, yet sell one to you anyway.Please do not contact me to criticize my pricing.  A certain amount of negotiation is to be expected, but don't expect anything unrealistic.  I have done my research.  Please have the courtesy to do the same. when making an offer.With all of that said, I can get on with discussing the gun itself.The Kel-Tec PF-9 is a subcompact 9mm (NOT .380, 9mm Makarov or 9mm Kurtz).  Its mode of fire is Double Action Only semi-automatic.  It feeds from a single stack magazine.The gun originally came with ONE 7 round magazine.  I bought a second 7 round magazine for it.  (I also bought a pinky rest for it as well, but didn't like it, took it off and have list it since then)I still have the original case.  I have a lock that feeds through the mag well or barrel and through the chamber as tamper prevention.The gun conceals well and sits comfortably in a pancake or ankle holster.  It is light enough that it is not incomfortable to carry around all day, whether in a car or walking around.  I have carried this gun and, in order to not be a danger to myself and others with it, I practiced with it.  It shoots and feeds reliably.  I never had a misfire and I never had the slide lock back with a round in the magazine.  In short, it's a well designed gun and is in good shape.  It has years of service left in it.  It has some holster wear, and it shows where the slide rubbed against the rivet in my jeans.  The difference between this gun and a new one is that I have already broken it in for you.
